    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Armenian Genocide</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Cross G Mooradian letter, commenting on September 27 World Briefing article, scores Clinton administration's opposition to House's effort to recognize and commemmorate Armenian genocide of 1915</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report (World Briefing item, Sept. 27) that the Clinton administration opposes the House's effort to recognize and commemorate the Armenian genocide of 1915 -- arguing that history should decide.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report (World Briefing item, Sept. 27) that the Clinton administration opposes the House's effort to recognize and commemorate the Armenian genocide of 1915 -- arguing that history should decide.</p>
        <p>Well, the historical judgment is already in from Elie Wiesel and 125 other historians and Holocaust scholars who recognize it as an ''incontestable historical fact,'' and ''urge Western democracies to officially recognize it.'' The Clinton administration need only find morals enough to enforce this verdict.</p>
        <p>CROSS G. MOORADIAN  Detroit, Sept. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
